Neither Ferrerius, Lindsay of Pitscottie‚ nor Lesly describe it: but, according to Buchanan‚ the King was led away from the Exchequer on the pretext of a hunting party, and Lord Kennedy, being one of those in his company, beginning to suspect treachery, attempted a rescue, but was overborne by a blow dealt at him by Sir Alexander Boyd. We now know that Kennedy was himself a party to the scheme : but that he made a seint of opposition‚ and submitted to a brief imprisonment in the Castle of Stirling for appear- ance sake, is rendered probable by two incidental allusions in the accounts of the following year to ale that was brewed and drunk in Stirling Castle, at the time of, or immediately after, the arrest of Gilbert Lord Kennedy.3
